{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533074"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:32:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:32:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14750"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14750"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.03,0.09,0.64,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58402"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7441"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43824"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"226"},{"type":"tags","id":"278"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2253"},{"type":"tags","id":"2471"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"5967"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18217"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58402"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with progressive shortness of breath over three days. She has a medical history of obesity with a BMI of 45 kg/m2, obstructive sleep apnoea and lymphoedema. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears drowsy. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She has reduced air entry bilaterally with coarse breath sounds. Arterial blood gas reveals pH 7.28 (7.35-7.45), PaCO2 68 mmHg (35-45), PaO2 58 mmHg (80-100), and bicarbonate 32 mmol/L (22-26).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High-flow nasal oxygen","Intravenous furosemide","Supplemental oxygen via nasal cannula","Non-invasive ventilation with BiPAP","Intubation and mechanical ventilation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute on chronic respiratory failure due to obesity hypoventilation syndrome (OHS), characterised by obesity, daytime hypercapnia, and sleep-disordered breathing. The arterial blood gas shows acute respiratory acidosis with chronic compensation (elevated bicarbonate).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-invasive ventilation with BiPAP\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. BiPAP provides both inspiratory and expiratory pressure support, which helps overcome upper airway resistance, improves alveolar ventilation, and reduces work of breathing. It is particularly effective in OHS as it addresses both the obstructive and restrictive components of the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-flow nasal oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not adequately address the ventilatory failure and hypercapnia. While it can provide some positive end-expiratory pressure, it does not provide the level of ventilatory support needed in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntubation and mechanical ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive as initial management unless there are signs of severe respiratory failure, decreased consciousness, or haemodynamic instability. Non-invasive ventilation should be tried first if the patient is able to protect their airway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the primary problem of ventilatory failure. While the patient may have some fluid overload, the priority is to support ventilation and oxygenation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupplemental oxygen via nasal cannula\u003C/strong\u003E alone could worsen hypercapnia by reducing respiratory drive and would not address the underlying ventilatory failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELong-term management should focus on weight loss through lifestyle modifications and possibly bariatric surgery, along with ongoing nocturnal ventilatory support.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Obesity hypoventilation syndrome is characterised by obesity (BMI \u003E30 kg/m2), daytime hypercapnia (PaCO2 \u003E45 mmHg), and sleep-disordered breathing.","BiPAP is the first-line treatment for acute respiratory failure in obesity hypoventilation syndrome."],"references":["Mokhlesi B, Masa JF, Brozek JL, Gurubhagavatula I, Murphy PB, Piper AJ, Tulaimat A. Evaluation and Management of Obesity Hypoventilation Syndrome. An Official American Thoracic Society Clinical Practice Guideline. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2019 Aug 1;200(3):e6-e24. doi: 10.1164/rccm.201905-1071ST. Erratum in: Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2019 Nov 15;200(10):1326. doi: 10.1164/rccm.v200erratum7. PMID: 31368798; PMCID: PMC6680300.","Antoine MH, Sankari A, Bollu PC. Obesity-Hypoventilation Syndrome. [Updated 2024 Jan 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482300/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43824"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14750"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43824"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-31T15:45:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T15:46:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7441"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58402"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"up